<p><span class="slidev-note-click-mark" data-clicks="1"></span> We've seen functions that never return, like our error-throwing friend from earlier.
<span class="slidev-note-click-mark" data-clicks="2"></span> It also appears in code branches that should be unreachable. If TypeScript sees 'never', it's saying &quot;this code should never run!&quot;
<span class="slidev-note-click-mark" data-clicks="3"></span> In switch statements, 'never' helps us ensure we've covered all our bases.
<span class="slidev-note-click-mark" data-clicks="4"></span> And in some type operations, like empty arrays or intersections of types that can't coexist, 'never' pops up.
<span class="slidev-note-click-mark" data-clicks="5"></span> But why should we care? Let's look at the power of 'never':
<span class="slidev-note-click-mark" data-clicks="6"></span> It's great at catching logical errors. If you see 'never' where you don't expect it, something's probably wrong!
<span class="slidev-note-click-mark" data-clicks="7"></span> It ensures you've handled all possible cases in your code. No more forgotten edge cases!
<span class="slidev-note-click-mark" data-clicks="8"></span> It allows you to make certain states in your program truly impossible at the type level.
<span class="slidev-note-click-mark" data-clicks="9"></span> In complex scenarios, 'never' enhances type safety by eliminating impossible cases.</p>
